    <!-- SECTION 10: India use-case recommendations -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-ink mb-5 mt-12">10. Our Recommendations for India</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-10">
      <div class="rounded-xl border-l-4 border-brand-red bg-brand-pale p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
          <span class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-brand-red bg-brand-red/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded">Industrial & Commercial (100 kW+)</span>
        </div>
        <p class="font-bold text-neutral-ink mb-1">Specify TOPCon bifacial</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-muted">The cost-to-performance ratio is unmatched in 2025. At ₹75/Wp vs PERC's ₹47/Wp, the premium pays back within 3–4 years through higher yields and lower degradation. ALMM-listed TOPCon modules from Adani, Trina, or LONGi are the default choice for RESCO and captive power projects.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-l-4 border-neutral-ink bg-neutral-snow p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
          <span class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-ink bg-neutral-ink/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded">Rajasthan, Gujarat, Andhra</span>
        </div>
        <p class="font-bold text-neutral-ink mb-1">HJT justifies its premium</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-muted">In India's hottest states, peak module temperatures exceed 75 °C. HJT's thermal advantage over PERC translates to 4–6% more annual energy. For a 500 kW system in Ahmedabad, that's roughly ₹18–25 lakh in additional revenue annually. Over 25 years, HJT's higher upfront cost is recovered several times over.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-l-4 border-brand-red/50 bg-white border p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
          <span class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-brand-red/70 bg-brand-pale px-2 py-0.5 rounded">Residential (1–10 kW)</span>
        </div>
        <p class="font-bold text-neutral-ink mb-1">TOPCon with PM Surya Ghar subsidy</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-muted">For homes installing under PM Surya Ghar Muft Bijli Yojana, TOPCon gives the best module efficiency in the smallest roof footprint while remaining ALMM-compliant for subsidy eligibility. The ₹78,000 central subsidy on a 3 kW system largely absorbs the PERC-to-TOPCon premium.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border-l-4 border-neutral-muted bg-white border p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
          <span class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-muted bg-neutral-snow px-2 py-0.5 rounded">Avoid</span>
        </div>
        <p class="font-bold text-neutral-ink mb-1">Mono PERC for any new installation after 2025</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-muted">PERC is not bad technology — it's just been surpassed. The concern is medium-term: as manufacturers pivot to n-type, warranty support and replacement panel availability for PERC systems will become harder to guarantee by 2028–2030. If your system is designed to last 25 years, don't specify a technology being discontinued now.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 11: What's next -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-ink mb-4 mt-12">11. What's Coming Next — Perovskite Tandem</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
      No technology overview in 2025 is complete without mentioning the coming disruption.
      <strong>Perovskite-silicon tandem cells</strong> — which stack a perovskite top cell over a
      silicon bottom cell — have already achieved 33.9% efficiency in laboratory conditions (LONGi,
      2024), shattering the 29.4% theoretical single-junction silicon limit.
    </p>
    <p class="text-neutral-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Commercial tandem modules are not yet available at scale. Durability under UV exposure,
      humidity, and temperature cycling remains the primary barrier. Most analysts project first
      commercial availability between 2027–2030, with mass-market adoption a further 2–3 years beyond.
    </p>
    <div class="rounded-xl bg-neutral-snow border border-neutral-rule p-5 mb-10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-muted mb-3">Technology Efficiency Roadmap</p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 text-xs">
        {[
          { label: 'Poly (commercial)', val: '16.5%', color: 'bg-neutral-200 text-neutral-muted' },
          { label: 'PERC (commercial)', val: '21.3%', color: 'bg-brand-red/20 text-brand-red' },
          { label: 'TOPCon (commercial)', val: '23.3%', color: 'bg-brand-red text-white' },
          { label: 'HJT (commercial)', val: '24.3%', color: 'bg-neutral-800 text-white' },
          { label: 'HJT (lab record)', val: '27.09%', color: 'bg-neutral-900 text-white' },
          { label: 'Tandem (lab record)', val: '33.9%', color: 'bg-green-700 text-white' },
          { label: 'Tandem (theoretical)', val: '47%+', color: 'bg-green-900 text-white' },
        ].map((item) => (
          <div class={`px-3 py-2 rounded-lg ${item.color} font-medium`}>
            {item.label}: <strong>{item.val}</strong>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="text-xs text-neutral-muted mt-3">Source: NREL Solar Cell Efficiency Tables Version 64 (2024)</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Conclusion -->
    <div class="rounded-2xl bg-neutral-ink p-8 mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Conclusion</h2>
      <p class="text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The solar panel market has effectively bifurcated into a transition moment: everything
        built before 2023 was largely PERC; everything being built now is n-type (TOPCon + HJT).
        Polycrystalline is a historical footnote.
      </p>
      <p class="text-white/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        For Indian buyers, the technology choice is not just an efficiency question — it's a
        thermodynamics question. Our climate actively punishes panels with poor temperature
        coefficients. A panel that loses 15% of its output on every hot summer day, year after year,
        is a different proposition than one that loses 10%.
      </p>
      <p class="text-white/80 leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-white">Our recommendation is clear:</strong> default to TOPCon for the
        vast majority of Indian projects, and specify HJT for premium or high-temperature-stress
        deployments. The extra capital cost pays back through electricity units — and in India,
        with decades of high tariff inflation ahead, every unit counts.
      </p>
    </div>

